    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div type="letter">
                <div type="text">
                    <div type="transcription">
                        <p>I cannot doubt about animals reasoning in a practical fashion. The case of rats is very curious. Do not they hear the water trickling?<ref target="#foot.f2"/></p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                
                
            </div>
            
            
            <div type="footnotes">
                <note xml:id="foot.f1">The date is established by the relationship between this fragment and the <ref target="./DCP-LETT-10255.xml">letter from Arthur Nicols, 10 November 1875</ref> (<hi rend="italic">Correspondence</hi> vol. 23).</note>
                <note xml:id="foot.f2">This quotation from CD’s letter was published in <hi rend="italic">Nature</hi> in a letter from Nicols headed ‘Intellect in brutes’, describing how rats gnawed small holes in lead pipes in a house in order to access clean water; Nicols had wondered how the rats knew there was water in the pipes (see also <hi rend="italic">Correspondence</hi> vol. 23, <ref target="./DCP-LETT-10253.xml">letter from Arthur Nicols, [before 10 November 1875]</ref>).</note>
            </div>
        
